18 SECTION 9. IC 25-1-1.1-6, AS AMENDED BY P.L.93-2024,
19 SECTION 177, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS
20 [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 6. (a) This section applies to a
21 license or certificate under this title that is in effect on July 1, 2018, or
22 created on or established after that date.
23 (b) As used in this section, "crime" has the meaning set forth in
24 IC 33-23-1-4.
25 (c) As used in this section, "criminal history information" has the
26 meaning set forth in IC 5-2-4-1.
27 (d) Not later than November 1, 2018, a board, commission, or
28 committee shall revise its licensing or certification requirements to the
29 extent necessary to explicitly list the crimes that may disqualify an
30 individual from receiving a license or certificate under this title. The
31 board, commission, or committee may not:
32 (1) use nonspecific terms, such as moral turpitude or good
33 character, as a licensing or certification requirement; or
34 (2) consider an arrest that does not result in a conviction.
35 (e) A board's, commission's, or committee's use of an individual's
36 conviction of a crime as a conviction of concern is limited to a crime
37 directly related to the duties and responsibilities of the occupation or
38 profession for which the individual is applying for or holds a license or
39 certification.
40 (f) If an individual has a conviction of concern, the period of
41 disqualification may not exceed five (5) years after the date of the
42 conviction, unless the individual:
EH 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

13
1 (1) was convicted of a crime of violence (as defined by
2 IC 35-50-1-2(a)); IC 35-31.5-2-79);
3 (2) was convicted of an offense relating to a criminal sexual act
4 (as defined by IC 35-31.5-2-216); or
5 (3) is convicted of a second or subsequent crime during the
6 disqualification period.
7 (g) An individual having a conviction of concern may at any time
8 petition a board, commission, or committee requiring a license or
9 certificate for a determination as to whether the individual's conviction
10 of concern will disqualify the individual from receiving the license or
11 certification. An individual filing a petition under this subsection shall
12 submit the following:
13 (1) At no expense to the state, a national criminal background
14 check by the Federal Bureau of Investigation.
15 (2) Any additional information requested by the board,
16 commission, or committee to assist the board, commission, or
17 committee in its review of the individual's petition.
18 (h) If an individual has a conviction of concern, the board,
19 commission, or committee shall consider the following in determining
20 whether to deny a license or certification to the individual based on the
21 following factors:
22 (1) The nature and seriousness of the crime for which the
23 individual was convicted.
24 (2) The passage of time since the commission of the crime.
25 (3) The relationship of the crime to the ability, capacity, and
26 fitness required to perform the duties and discharge the
27 responsibilities of the occupation.
28 (4) Evidence of rehabilitation or treatment undertaken by the
29 individual that might mitigate against a direct relation to the
30 ability, capacity, and fitness required to perform the duties and
31 discharge the responsibilities of the occupation.
32 (i) If a board, commission, or committee determines an individual's
33 conviction of concern disqualifies the individual from receiving a
34 license or certification solely or in part because of the individual's
35 criminal history, the board, commission, or committee shall notify the
36 individual in writing of the following:
37 (1) The grounds and reasons for the denial or disqualification.
38 (2) The individual has the right to a hearing to challenge the
39 licensing authority's decision.
40 (3) The earliest date the individual may reapply for a license or
41 certification or the earliest date the individual can petition the
42 board, commission, or committee for a review.
EH 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

14
1 (4) Evidence of rehabilitation may be considered upon
2 reapplication.
3 (5) Findings for each of the factors specified in subdivisions (1)
4 through (4).
5 Any written determination that an individual's criminal history contains
6 a conviction of concern that merits the denial of a license must be
7 documented in written findings under subdivision (1) by clear and
8 convincing evidence sufficient for review by a court. In an
9 administrative hearing or a civil action reviewing the denial of a
10 license, a board, commission, or committee has the burden of proof on
11 the question of whether the individual's criminal history, based on the
12 standards provided in subsection (h), should lead to the denial of a
13 license.
14 (j) The board, commission, or committee shall inform the individual
15 of its determination concerning the individual's petition not later than
16 sixty (60) days after the petition, criminal history information, and any
17 other information requested under subsection (g) is received by the
18 board, commission, or committee.
19 (k) The board, commission, or committee may charge a fee
20 established under IC 25-1-8 that does not exceed twenty-five dollars
21 ($25) to pay its costs of reviewing a petition filed under subsection (g).
22 (l) A board, commission, or committee may adopt rules under
23 IC 4-22-2 to implement this section.
24 SECTION 10. IC 25-23.6-1-5.7, AS AMENDED BY P.L.142-2020,
25 SECTION 27, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
26 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 5.7. (a) "Practice of addiction counseling" means
27 the providing of professional services that are delivered by a licensed
28 addiction counselor, that are designed to change substance use or
29 addictive behavior, and that involve specialized knowledge and skill
30 related to addictions and addictive behaviors, including understanding
31 addiction, knowledge of the treatment process, application to practice,
32 and professional readiness. The term includes:
33 (1) gathering information through structured interview screens
34 using routine protocols;
35 (2) reviewing assessment findings to assist in the development of
36 a plan individualized for treatment services and to coordinate
37 services;
38 (3) referring for assessment, diagnosis, evaluation, and mental
39 health therapy;
40 (4) providing client and family education related to addictions;
41 (5) providing information on social networks and community
42 systems for referrals and discharge planning;
EH 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

15
1 (6) participating in multidisciplinary treatment team meetings or
2 consulting with clinical addiction professionals;
3 (7) counseling, through individual and group counseling, as well
4 as group and family education, to treat addiction and substance
5 abuse in a variety of settings, including:
6 (A) mental and physical health facilities; and
7 (B) child and family service agencies; and
8 (8) maintaining the highest level of professionalism and ethical
9 responsibility.
10 (b) The term does not include the use of psychotherapy or diagnosis
11 (as defined in IC 25-22.5-1-1.1(c) or as defined as the practice of
12 psychology under IC 25-33-1-2(a)).
13 (c) For an individual who obtains a license as an addiction counselor
14 by:
15 (1) holding a valid:
16 (A) level II or higher certification or the equivalent
17 certification from a credentialing agency approved by the
18 division of mental health and addiction; or
19 (B) certification as an addiction counselor or addiction
20 therapist from a credentialing agency that is approved by the
21 board;
22 (2) having at least ten (10) years of experience in addiction
23 counseling;
24 (3) furnishing satisfactory evidence to the board that the
25 individual does not have:
26 (A) a conviction for a crime of violence (as defined in
27 IC 35-50-1-2); IC 35-31.5-2-79); or
28 (B) a conviction in the previous two (2) years that has a direct
29 bearing on the individual's ability to practice competently; and
30 (4) filing an initial application with the board before July 1, 2010;
31 the term includes the provision of addiction counseling services in
32 private practice in consultation with other licensed professionals as
