22 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 1.3. (a) For purposes of this chapter, "advisory
23 sentence" means a guideline sentence that the court may voluntarily
24 consider when imposing a sentence.
25 (b) Except as provided in subsection (c), a court is not required to
26 use an advisory sentence.
27 (c) In imposing:
28 (1) consecutive sentences for felony convictions that are not
29 crimes of violence (as defined in IC 35-50-1-2(a))
30 IC 35-31.5-2-79) arising out of an episode of criminal conduct,
31 in accordance with IC 35-50-1-2; or
32 (2) an additional fixed term to a repeat sexual offender under
33 section 14 of this chapter;
34 a court is required to use the appropriate advisory sentence in imposing
35 a consecutive sentence or an additional fixed term. However, the court
36 is not required to use the advisory sentence in imposing the sentence
37 for the underlying offense.
38 (d) This section does not require a court to use an advisory sentence
39 in imposing consecutive sentences for felony convictions that do not
40 arise out of an episode of criminal conduct.
41 SECTION 27. IC 35-50-6-1, AS AMENDED BY P.L.20-2023,
42 SECTION 1, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
EH 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

37
1 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 1. (a) Except as provided in subsection (d) or (e),
2 when a person imprisoned for a felony completes the person's term of
3 imprisonment, less the credit time the person has earned with respect
4 to that term, the person shall be:
5 (1) released on parole for not more than twenty-four (24) months,
6 as determined by the parole board, unless:
7 (A) the person is being placed on parole for the first time;
8 (B) the person is not being placed on parole following a term
9 of imprisonment that includes a sentence imposed for a crime
10 of violence (as defined in IC 35-50-1-2); IC 35-31.5-2-79);
11 (C) the person is not a sex offender (as defined in
12 IC 11-8-8-4.5); and
13 (D) in the six (6) months before being placed on parole, the
14 person has not violated a rule of the department of correction
15 or a rule of the penal facility in which the person is
16 imprisoned;
17 (2) discharged upon a finding by the committing court that the
18 person was assigned to a community transition program and may
19 be discharged without the requirement of parole; or
20 (3) released to the committing court if the sentence included a
21 period of probation.
22 A person described in subdivision (1) shall be released on parole for
23 not more than twelve (12) months, as determined by the parole board.
24 (b) This subsection does not apply to a person described in
25 subsection (d), (e), or (f). A person released on parole remains on
26 parole from the date of release until the person's fixed term expires,
27 unless the person's parole is revoked or the person is discharged from
28 that term by the parole board. In any event, if the person's parole is not
29 revoked, the parole board shall discharge the person after the period set
30 under subsection (a) or the expiration of the person's fixed term,
31 whichever is shorter.
32 (c) A person whose parole is revoked shall be imprisoned for all or
33 part of the remainder of the person's fixed term. However, the person
34 shall again be released on parole when the person completes that
35 remainder, less the credit time the person has earned since the
36 revocation. The parole board may reinstate the person on parole at any
37 time after the revocation.
38 (d) This subsection does not apply to a person who is a sexually
39 violent predator under IC 35-38-1-7.5. When a sex offender (as defined
40 in IC 11-8-8-4.5) completes the sex offender's fixed term of
41 imprisonment, less credit time earned with respect to that term, the sex
42 offender shall be placed on parole for not more than ten (10) years.
EH 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

38
1 (e) This subsection applies to a person who:
2 (1) is a sexually violent predator under IC 35-38-1-7.5;
3 (2) has been convicted of murder (IC 35-42-1-1); or
4 (3) has been convicted of voluntary manslaughter (IC 35-42-1-3).
5 When a person described in this subsection completes the person's
6 fixed term of imprisonment, less credit time earned with respect to that
7 term, the person shall be placed on parole for the remainder of the
8 person's life.
9 (f) This subsection applies to a parolee in another jurisdiction who
10 is a person described in subsection (e) and whose parole supervision is
11 transferred to Indiana from another jurisdiction. In accordance with
12 IC 11-13-4-1(2) (Interstate Compact for Out-of-State Probationers and
13 Parolees) and rules adopted under Article VII (d)(8) of the Interstate
14 Compact for Adult Offender Supervision (IC 11-13-4.5), a parolee who
15 is a person described in subsection (e) and whose parole supervision is
16 transferred to Indiana is subject to the same conditions of parole as a
17 person described in subsection (e) who was convicted in Indiana,
18 including:
19 (1) lifetime parole (as described in subsection (e)); and
20 (2) the requirement that the person wear a monitoring device (as
21 described in IC 35-38-2.5-3) that can transmit information
22 twenty-four (24) hours each day regarding a person's precise
23 location, if applicable.
24 (g) If a person being supervised on lifetime parole as described in
25 subsection (e) is also required to be supervised by a court, a probation
26 department, a community corrections program, a community transition
27 program, or another similar program upon the person's release from
28 imprisonment, the parole board may:
29 (1) supervise the person while the person is being supervised by
30 the other supervising agency; or
31 (2) permit the other supervising agency to exercise all or part of
32 the parole board's supervisory responsibility during the period in
33 which the other supervising agency is required to supervise the
34 person, if supervision by the other supervising agency will be, in
35 the opinion of the parole board:
36 (A) at least as stringent; and
37 (B) at least as effective;
38 as supervision by the parole board.
39 (h) The parole board is not required to supervise a person on
40 lifetime parole during any period in which the person is imprisoned.
41 However, upon the person's release from imprisonment, the parole
42 board shall recommence its supervision of a person on lifetime parole.
EH 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

39
1 (i) If a court orders the parole board to place a sexually violent
2 predator whose sentence does not include a commitment to the
3 department of correction on lifetime parole under IC 35-38-1-29, the
4 parole board shall place the sexually violent predator on lifetime parole
5 and supervise the person in the same manner in which the parole board
6 supervises a sexually violent predator on lifetime parole whose
7 sentence includes a commitment to the department of correction.
8 (j) Time served while confined to a jail or prison does not count
9 toward time served on parole.
10 SECTION 28. IC 36-1-26-4, AS ADDED BY P.L.182-2018,
11 SECTION 6, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
12 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 4. (a) Not later than November 1, 2018, a unit
13 shall revise its licensing requirements to the extent necessary to
14 explicitly list the crimes that will disqualify an individual from
15 receiving a license required by the unit. The unit may not:
16 (1) use nonspecific terms, such as moral turpitude or good
17 character, as a licensing requirement; or
18 (2) consider an arrest that does not result in a conviction.
19 (b) A unit's use of an individual's conviction of a crime as a
20 disqualifying criminal conviction is limited to a crime that is
21 specifically and directly related to the duties and responsibilities of the
22 occupation or profession for which the individual is applying for or
23 holds a license.
24 (c) If an applicant has a disqualifying criminal history, the unit shall
25 consider the following in determining whether to deny a license to the
26 applicant, based on a clear and convincing showing:
27 (1) The nature and seriousness of the crime for which the
28 individual was convicted.
29 (2) The passage of time since the commission of the crime.
30 (3) The relationship of the crime to the ability, capacity, and
31 fitness required to perform the duties and discharge the
32 responsibilities of the occupation.
33 (4) Evidence of rehabilitation or treatment undertaken by the
34 individual that might mitigate against a direct relation to the
35 ability, capacity, and fitness required to perform the duties and
36 discharge the responsibilities of the occupation.
37 (d) If an individual has a disqualifying criminal conviction, the
38 period of disqualification may not exceed five (5) years after the date
39 of the conviction or release from incarceration, whichever is later,
40 unless the individual:
41 (1) was convicted of a crime of violence (as defined by
42 IC 35-50-1-2(a)); IC 35-31.5-2-79);
EH 1258—LS 6822/DI 151

40
1 (2) was convicted of an offense relating to a criminal sexual act
2 (as defined by IC 35-31.5-2-216); or
3 (3) is convicted of a second or subsequent crime during the
4 disqualification period.
5 SECTION 29. IC 36-8-26-6, AS ADDED BY P.L.103-2022,
6 SECTION 6, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
7 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 6. Before November 1, 2023, and before
8 November 1 of every year thereafter, the board shall send a report of its
9 activities to the legislative council. The report must be in an electronic
10 format under IC 5-14-6 and include the following information:
11 (1) A copy of every interoperability agreement entered into or
12 renewed in the past year.
13 (2) A list of all:
14 (A) Part One crimes (based on the reporting methodology of
15 the Federal Bureau of Investigation); and
16 (B) crimes of violence (as defined in IC 35-50-1-2(a));
17 IC 35-31.5-2-79);
18 committed in the downtown district within the previous five (5)
19 years.
20 (3) The crime clearance rates for each crime described in
21 subdivision (2).
22 (4) A list of every major event that took place in the downtown
23 district within the previous year.
24 (5) The number of times a law enforcement agency made a
25 referral to, or requested assistance from, a social worker or mental
26 health services provider (including a provider who specializes in
27 addiction services).
28 (6) A completed crime perception survey for the previous year
29 (based on the survey prepared by Downtown Indy, Inc.).
